  "fun_facts": [
    "E514i in its hydrated form is known as 'Glauber's salt' - named after Johann Glauber who discovered it in 1625",
    "Glauber's salt was historically used as a laxative and is still used medicinally for bowel cleansing",
    "Has an unusual property: it dissolves in water with cooling (endothermic reaction) rather than heating",
    "Used more in industrial food processing than as a direct food ingredient",
    "The anhydrous form is also called 'salt cake' in industrial applications",
    "Relatively rare in modern food products - more commonly found in industrial and pharmaceutical uses"
  ]
